## Component Conversion Patterns

### 1. React Router Page → Inertia Page Component

**Before (React SPA):**

```jsx
// src/pages/Products.jsx
function Products() {
    const [products, setProducts] = useState([]);

    useEffect(() => {
        fetch('/api/products').then(r => r.json()).then(setProducts);
    }, []);

    return <div>{products.map(p => <ProductCard key={p.id} product={p} />)}</div>;
}
```

**After (Inertia Page + Laravel Controller):**

```php
// app/Http/Controllers/ProductController.php
use Inertia\Inertia;

class ProductController extends Controller
{
    public function index(): \Inertia\Response
    {
        return Inertia::render('Products/Index', [
            'products' => Product::all(),
        ]);
    }
}
```

```jsx
// resources/js/Pages/Products/Index.jsx
export default function ProductsIndex({ products }) {
    return (
        <div>
            {products.map(p => (
                <ProductCard key={p.id} product={p} />
            ))}
        </div>
    );
}
```

> No `useState` + `useEffect` + `fetch` needed. Laravel passes data directly as React props.

---

### 2. React Router → Laravel Routes + Inertia Links

**Before:**

```jsx
// React Router
import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

<Link to="/products">Products</Link>
<Link to={`/products/${id}`}>View</Link>
```

**After:**

```jsx
// Inertia Link (handles client-side navigation without full reload)
import { Link } from '@inertiajs/react';

<Link href="/products">Products</Link>
<Link href={route('products.show', id)}>View</Link>
```

Laravel route:

```php
// routes/web.php
Route::get('/products', [ProductController::class, 'index'])->name('products.index');
Route::get('/products/{product}', [ProductController::class, 'show'])->name('products.show');
```

> Install `ziggy` (`tightenco/ziggy`) to use `route()` helper in JavaScript.

---

### 3. Persistent Layout

**Before (React Router Layout):**

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <Router>
            <Navbar />
            <Routes>
                <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
            </Routes>
        </Router>
    );
}
```

**After (Inertia Persistent Layout):**

```jsx
// resources/js/Layouts/AppLayout.jsx
export default function AppLayout({ children }) {
    return (
        <div>
            <Navbar />
            <main>{children}</main>
        </div>
    );
}
```

```jsx
// resources/js/Pages/Home.jsx
import AppLayout from '@/Layouts/AppLayout';

export default function Home({ featuredProducts }) {
    return <div>{/* page content */}</div>;
}

// Attach layout — persists across Inertia navigation (Navbar doesn't remount)
// This is a *render callback* (receives the page element). That pattern is fine in v3.
Home.layout = page => <AppLayout>{page}</AppLayout>;
```

#### Inertia v3 — layout assignment caveat

In v3 you **cannot** assign an **arrow function component** directly to `.layout` — Inertia cannot tell it apart from a render function. Prefer a **function declaration**, wrap the component in an **array**, or set a **default layout** in `createInertiaApp` ([upgrade guide — React layouts](https://inertiajs.com/docs/v3/getting-started/upgrade-guide.md)):

```jsx
// ❌ Broken in v3 — Layout is an arrow *component* assigned directly
const Layout = ({ children }) => <main>{children}</main>;
Dashboard.layout = Layout;

// ✅ Wrap in an array
Dashboard.layout = [Layout];

// ✅ Or use a function declaration for the layout component
function Layout({ children }) {
    return <main>{children}</main>;
}
Dashboard.layout = Layout;
```

The `Page.layout = page => <AppLayout>{page}</AppLayout>` pattern above is a **function that returns JSX** (render callback), not “assign arrow component reference”, so it remains a common valid approach.

